Which are categorical variables (numeric or character variables with variables that have a fixed and known set of possible values; aka factor variables)?

The three character types and year have set possible values:
* year (16) [2000-2015]
+ technically of type but since its a year, they must be ints within bounded possible years (eg no years before XX and no years after 2018 -today!) so it can be treated as a factor. Not sure if youd want to or not though.
* country (206)
* continent (5)
* region (22)

yrs <- data %>% distinct(year) %>% count()
cntry <- data %>% distinct(country) %>% count()
cntnt <- data %>% distinct(continent) %>% count()
rgn <- data %>% distinct(region) %>% count()

Part 3 -

Your goal during EDA is to develop an understanding of your data. The easiest way to do this is to use questions as tools to guide your investigation.EDA is fundamentally a creative process. And like most creative processes, the key to asking quality questions is to generate a large quantity of questions.

Im going to add a little bit here to explore the data, initially, like the example does: Visualize Max/Mins and distribution by continent. This violin plot is my new favorite. Especially overlaying a point distribution of the data on top.

From this graph, we can see that while europe is by far the highest on average, it has a few countries that dont drink much at all. Additionally, while asia is predominantly non-drinking, there are a few that compete with even the highest of europe and has the most significant range of values. Oceania, has a fairly odd distribution that looks like two separate populations and may be described by the indonesian countries that are more similar to asia and the western countries (Australia, NZ, Tazmania) Needs some more exploration to say for sure. Americas have a pretty interestingly tight distribution and Africa has a noticeably significant range of values.

data_jnd %>% filter(!is.na(x1)) %>% group_by(continent) %>% ggplot(aes(x = continent, y = x1, color=continent )) + geom_violin() + geom_point()

task 1

How does [alcohol consumption] (x1) vary across different continents?

# what years does this include? 
data_jnd %>% filter(!is.na(x1), !is.na(gdp_per_cap)) %>% select(year) %>% summary() 
##       year     
##  Min.   :2000  
##  1st Qu.:2005  
##  Median :2005  
##  Mean   :2006  
##  3rd Qu.:2008  
##  Max.   :2008
# lets create median of the years available 
data3 <- data_jnd %>% filter(!is.na(x1), !is.na(gdp_per_cap)) %>% group_by(continent) %>% summarize(med_x1 = median(x1), med_gdp = median(gdp_per_cap)) 
# get rid of med_gdp, we'll use that next. Generate table
dg <- data3 %>% select(-med_gdp)
dg
## # A tibble: 5 x 2
##   continent med_x1
##   <chr>      <dbl>
## 1 Africa      3.78
## 2 Americas    6.91
## 3 Asia        2.47
## 4 Europe     12.5 
## 5 Oceania     3.71
#plot a bar plot 
dg %>% ggplot(aes(x=continent, y=med_x1, fill= continent)) + geom_col() + ggtitle("Alcohol consumption by continent")

From this table and chart, we can show that between the years of 2000 and 2008, the median liters of alcohol consumed per person per year varied significantly between continents. Europe was by far the leader in alcohol consumption, with americas being just under half as much. The remaining countries were all about half of the americas.

task 2 : how do countries alcohol consumption change over time?

Find countries with interesting stories. Open-ended and, therefore, hard. Promising but unsuccessful attempts are encouraged. This will generate interesting questions to follow up on in class.

data4 <-  data_jnd %>% filter(!is.na(x1), !is.na(gdp_per_cap)) %>% group_by(country)
data4 %>% ggplot(aes(x=year, y=x1, color=country)) + geom_line() + ggtitle("country alcohol consumption over time") + theme(legend.position = "none")

Whoops! But very interesting, we only have one country with data from 2000 to 2008, the rest only span from 2005 - 2008. Ill filter to only include 2005-2008. Also, there are way too many countries to compare this way, so well filter to just Africa. Lastly, there is very little change over the years in countries with x1 less than 5 so well only include countries with x1 > 5.

task 3 - does alc consumption correllate to gdp_per_cap?

data4 %>% ggplot(aes(x=x1, y=gdp_per_cap, color=year)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("alc consumption vs gdp/cap") +  geom_smooth(method='lm')

mod <- lm(formula=x1~gdp_per_cap, data=data4)
summary(mod)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = x1 ~ gdp_per_cap, data = data4)
## 
## Residuals:

## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.502 on 343 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1136, Adjusted R-squared:  0.111 
## F-statistic: 43.95 on 1 and 343 DF,  p-value: 1.307e-10

It looks like there is weak correlation, but a residual analysis is definitely needed and I d guess that there really isnt much predictive value in this model. However, it does seem like there may be two different groupings of this data that follow more predicatble trends, simply, data above the fitted line and data below the fitted line might have better predictive succuess if they could be separated by another variable.

data4 %>% ggplot(aes(x=x1, y=gdp_per_cap, color=continent)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("alc consumption vs gdp/cap (by continent)") 

# remove europe
data4 %>% filter(continent != "Europe", continent != "Asia") %>% ggplot(aes(x=x1, y=gdp_per_cap)) + geom_point() + ggtitle("alc consumption vs gdp/cap in americas, africa, oceania") +  geom_smooth(method='lm') + scale_y_log10()

Coloring the plot by continent shows that a significant portion of the outlying data is from Europe and Asia, and by removing those, it looks like there is increased correllation, and more importantly a linear model would have more predictive value. Additionally, by scaling gdp_per_cap by log10, it creates a better distribution of values and shows the trend. There are a great number of reasons that could account for this, Id hazard that the most likely reasons stem from culture and/or production.
